{"title_page": "Aspergilloma", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Aspergilloma\n| synonyms        = Mycetoma, fungus ball\n| image           = Aspergillomas complicating tuberculosis.jpg\n| caption         = Aspergillomas complicating tuberculosis: multiple aspergillomas within large cavitary lesions of tuberculous origin.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical speciality)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = chest x-ray show tumour like opacity . Serology can be helpful .fungal hyphae seen on KoH mount and sputum culture grows fungus\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nAn '''aspergilloma''' is a clump of [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] which exists in a body cavity such as a [[paranasal sinuses|paranasal sinus]] or an organ such as the [[Human lung|lung]]. By definition, it is caused by [[fungus|fungi]] of the [[genus]] ''[[Aspergillus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aspergilloma|work=Medical Dictionary|publisher=TheFreeDictionary|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/Aspergilloma}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nPeople with aspergillomata typically remain [[Subclinical infection|asymptomatic]] until the condition is fairly advanced; in some cases even for decades. [[Medical diagnosis|Diagnosis]] is often made as a result of an [[Incidental findings|incidental finding]] on a chest X-ray or [[X-ray computed tomography|CT scan]] that may be performed as part of the workup for another unrelated condition. However, a small percentage of aspergillomata invade into a blood vessel which can result in bleeding. Thus, the most common symptom of associated with aspergillomata is coughing up blood ([[hemoptysis]]). This may result in life-threatening hemorrhage, though the amount of blood lost is usually inconsequential.\n\nAspergillomata can also form in other organs. They can form [[abscess]]es in solid organs such as the brain or kidney, usually in people who are immunocompromised. They can also develop within body cavities such as the sphenoid or paranasal sinuses,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.life-worldwide.org/fungal-diseases/fungus-ball-of-the-sinus/ |title = Life}}</ref> the [[ear canal]], and rarely on surfaces such as [[heart valve]]s.\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Aspergilloma histology.jpg|thumb|[[Histopathology]] of aspergilloma, [[H&E stain]]ing]]\nThe most common organ affected by aspergilloma is the lung. Aspergilloma mainly affects people with underlying [[Cavitary pneumonia|cavitary lung disease]] such as [[tuberculosis]],  [[sarcoidosis]], [[bronchiectasis]], [[cystic fibrosis]] and systemic [[immunodeficiency]]. ''[[Aspergillus fumigatus]]'', the most common causative species, is typically inhaled as small (2 to 3 [[micrometre|micron]]) [[spore]]s. The fungus settles in a cavity and is able to grow free from interference because critical elements of the [[Cell-mediated immunity|immune system]] are unable to penetrate into the cavity. As the fungus multiplies, it forms a ball, which incorporates dead tissue from the surrounding lung, mucus, and other debris.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Soubani AO, Chandrasekar PH|title=The clinical spectrum of pulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Chest|volume=121|issue=6|pages=1988\u20139|date=June 2002|pmid=12065367|doi=10.1378/chest.121.6.1988|url=http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12065367|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414164558/http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12065367|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nDiagnosis of aspergilloma is by serum IgE levels which are usually raised in this condition \n\n\n{{Empty section|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Treatment==\nMost cases of aspergilloma do not require treatment.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Treatment of diseases which increase the risk of aspergilloma, such as tuberculosis, may help to prevent their formation. In cases complicated by severe hemoptysis or other associated conditions such as [[pleural empyema]] or [[pneumothorax]], surgery may be required to remove the aspergilloma and the surrounding lung tissue by doing a lobectomy or other types of resection and thus stop the bleeding. There has been interest in treatment with antifungal medications such as [[itraconazole]], none has yet been shown to reliably eradicate aspergillomata.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nAlthough most fungi\u2014and especially ''Aspergillus''\u2014fail to grow in healthy human tissue, significant growth may occur in people whose [[adaptive immune system]] is compromised, such as those with [[chronic granulomatous disease]], who are undergoing [[chemotherapy]], or who have recently undergone a [[Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation|bone marrow transplantation]]. Within the lungs of such individuals, the fungal [[hypha]]e spread out as a spherical growth. With the restoration of normal defense mechanisms, [[Neutrophil granulocyte|neutrophils]] and [[lymphocyte]]s are attracted to the edge of the spherical fungal growth where they [[lysis|lyse]], releasing tissue-digesting enzymes as a normal function. A sphere of the infected lung is thus cleaved from the adjacent lung. This sphere flops around in the resulting cavity and is recognized on x-ray as a fungus ball. This process is beneficial as a potentially serious invasive fungal infection is converted into surface colonization. Although the fungus is inactivated in the process, surgeons may choose to operate to reduce the possibility of bleeding. Microscopic examination of surgically removed recently formed fungus balls clearly shows a sphere of dead lung containing fungal hyphae. Microscopic examination of older lesions reveals mummified tissue which may reveal faint residual lung or hyphal structures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Przyjemski|first1=CJ|last2=Mattii|first2=R|title=The Formation of Pulmonary Mycetomata|journal=Cancer|volume=46|pages=1701\u20131704|year=1980|doi=10.1002/1097-0142(19801001)46:7<1701::AID-CNCR2820460733>3.0.CO;2-4|pmid=6932257|issue=7}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 29065  \n|  ICD10           =  \n|  ICD9            =  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     =  \n|  eMedicineSubj   =  \n|  eMedicineTopic  =  \n|  MeshID          = \n}}\n\n[[Category:Lung disorders]]\n[[Category:Animal fungal diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Aspergilloma\n| synonyms        = Mycetoma, fungus ball\n| image           = Aspergillomas complicating tuberculosis.jpg\n| caption         = Aspergillomas complicating tuberculosis: multiple aspergillomas within large cavitary lesions of tuberculous origin.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical speciality)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = chest x-ray show tumour like opacity . Serology can be helpful .fungal hyphae seen on KoH mount and sputum culture grows fungus\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nAn '''aspergilloma''' is a clump of [[mold]] which exists in a body cavity such as a [[paranasal sinuses|paranasal sinus]] or an organ such as the [[Human lung|lung]]. By definition, it is caused by [[fungus|fungi]] of the [[genus]] ''[[Aspergillus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aspergilloma|work=Medical Dictionary|publisher=TheFreeDictionary|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/Aspergilloma}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nPeople with aspergillomata typically remain [[Subclinical infection|asymptomatic]] until the condition is fairly advanced; in some cases even for decades. [[Medical diagnosis|Diagnosis]] is often made as a result of an [[Incidental findings|incidental finding]] on a chest X-ray or [[X-ray computed tomography|CT scan]] that may be performed as part of the workup for another unrelated condition. However, a small percentage of aspergillomata invade into a blood vessel which can result in bleeding. Thus, the most common symptom of associated with aspergillomata is coughing up blood ([[hemoptysis]]). This may result in life-threatening hemorrhage, though the amount of blood lost is usually inconsequential.\n\nAspergillomata can also form in other organs. They can form [[abscess]]es in solid organs such as the brain or kidney, usually in people who are immunocompromised. They can also develop within body cavities such as the sphenoid or paranasal sinuses,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.life-worldwide.org/fungal-diseases/fungus-ball-of-the-sinus/ |title = Life}}</ref> the [[ear canal]], and rarely on surfaces such as [[heart valve]]s.\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Aspergilloma histology.jpg|thumb|[[Histopathology]] of aspergilloma, [[H&E stain]]ing]]\nThe most common organ affected by aspergilloma is the lung. Aspergilloma mainly affects people with underlying [[Cavitary pneumonia|cavitary lung disease]] such as [[tuberculosis]],  [[sarcoidosis]], [[bronchiectasis]], [[cystic fibrosis]] and systemic [[immunodeficiency]]. ''[[Aspergillus fumigatus]]'', the most common causative species, is typically inhaled as small (2 to 3 [[micrometre|micron]]) [[spore]]s. The fungus settles in a cavity and is able to grow free from interference because critical elements of the [[Cell-mediated immunity|immune system]] are unable to penetrate into the cavity. As the fungus multiplies, it forms a ball, which incorporates dead tissue from the surrounding lung, mucus, and other debris.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Soubani AO, Chandrasekar PH|title=The clinical spectrum of pulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Chest|volume=121|issue=6|pages=1988\u20139|date=June 2002|pmid=12065367|doi=10.1378/chest.121.6.1988|url=http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12065367|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414164558/http://www.chestjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12065367|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nDiagnosis of aspergilloma is by serum IgE levels which are usually raised in this condition \n\n\n{{Empty section|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Treatment==\nMost cases of aspergilloma do not require treatment.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Treatment of diseases which increase the risk of aspergilloma, such as tuberculosis, may help to prevent their formation. In cases complicated by severe hemoptysis or other associated conditions such as [[pleural empyema]] or [[pneumothorax]], surgery may be required to remove the aspergilloma and the surrounding lung tissue by doing a lobectomy or other types of resection and thus stop the bleeding. There has been interest in treatment with antifungal medications such as [[itraconazole]], none has yet been shown to reliably eradicate aspergillomata.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nAlthough most fungi\u2014and especially ''Aspergillus''\u2014fail to grow in healthy human tissue, significant growth may occur in people whose [[adaptive immune system]] is compromised, such as those with [[chronic granulomatous disease]], who are undergoing [[chemotherapy]], or who have recently undergone a [[Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation|bone marrow transplantation]]. Within the lungs of such individuals, the fungal [[hypha]]e spread out as a spherical growth. With the restoration of normal defense mechanisms, [[Neutrophil granulocyte|neutrophils]] and [[lymphocyte]]s are attracted to the edge of the spherical fungal growth where they [[lysis|lyse]], releasing tissue-digesting enzymes as a normal function. A sphere of the infected lung is thus cleaved from the adjacent lung. This sphere flops around in the resulting cavity and is recognized on x-ray as a fungus ball. This process is beneficial as a potentially serious invasive fungal infection is converted into surface colonization. Although the fungus is inactivated in the process, surgeons may choose to operate to reduce the possibility of bleeding. Microscopic examination of surgically removed recently formed fungus balls clearly shows a sphere of dead lung containing fungal hyphae. Microscopic examination of older lesions reveals mummified tissue which may reveal faint residual lung or hyphal structures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Przyjemski|first1=CJ|last2=Mattii|first2=R|title=The Formation of Pulmonary Mycetomata|journal=Cancer|volume=46|pages=1701\u20131704|year=1980|doi=10.1002/1097-0142(19801001)46:7<1701::AID-CNCR2820460733>3.0.CO;2-4|pmid=6932257|issue=7}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 29065  \n|  ICD10           =  \n|  ICD9            =  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     =  \n|  eMedicineSubj   =  \n|  eMedicineTopic  =  \n|  MeshID          = \n}}\n\n[[Category:Lung disorders]]\n[[Category:Animal fungal diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aspergilloma"}
{"title_page": "Euphorbia candelabrum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Euphorbia candelabrum 1.JPG\n|image_caption = ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' in the [[Serengeti]]\n|genus = Euphorbia\n|species = candelabrum\n|authority = [[Carl Georg Theodor Kotschy|Kotschy]]\n|synonyms =\n    {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Euphorbia calycina'' <small>N.E.Br.</small>\n*''Euphorbia confertiflora'' <small>Volkens</small>\n*''Euphorbia murielii'' <small>N.E.Br.</small>\n*''Euphorbia reinhardtii'' <small>Volkens</small>\n    }}\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/kew-78823\n|title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species\n|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n|}}\n\n'''''Euphorbia candelabrum''''' is a [[succulent]] species of [[plant]] in the family [[Euphorbiaceae]], one of several plants commonly known as '''[[candelabra tree]]'''.<ref>{{GRIN | accessdate = 12 January 2018}}</ref> It is closely related to 3 other species of ''[[Euphorbia]]'' in particular; ''[[Euphorbia ingens]]'' in the dry regions of South Africa, ''Euphorbia conspicua'' from western Angola, and ''[[Euphorbia abyssinica]]'' which is native to a number of countries including Sudan, Eritrea, Djibouti, Ethiopia and Somalia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=Euphorbia+candelabrum|title=Euphorbia candelabrum|last=Fern|first=Ken|date=|website=Tropical Plants Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIts Latin name derives from its growth habit, often considered to resemble the branching of a candelabrum. Candelabra trees can be found in dry deciduous and evergreen open wooded grasslands, on rocky slopes and on the rare occasion, termite mounds. As rates of rainfall decrease, so does ''Euphorbia candelabrum''<nowiki/>'s habitat range.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holland|first=P. G.|last2=Hove|first2=A. R. T.|date=1975-03-01|title=The distribution of euphorbia candelabrum in the Southern Rift Valley, Kenya|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02387877|journal=Vegetatio|language=en|volume=30|issue=1|pages=49\u201354|doi=10.1007/BF02387877|issn=1573-5052}}</ref> Trees typically grow to be 12 metres in height however some specimens have been recorded to grow up to 20 metres tall.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''E. candelabrum'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Horn of Africa]] and eastern [[Africa]] along the [[East African Rift]] system. It is known in [[Ethiopia]] by its [[Amharic language|Amharic]] name, ''qwolqwal'', or its [[Oromo language|Oromo]] name, ''{{lang|om|adaamii}}''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Workineh Kelbessa<!-- see [[Habesha name]] -->|title=Traditional Oromo Attitudes towards the Environment: An Argument for Environmentally Sound Development|journal=Social Science Research Report Series|issue=19|year=2001|page=44|url=http://www.publications.ossrea.net/images/stories/ossrea/ssrr-19-p-5.pdf|format=PDF| accessdate={{Date|2014-02-04}} }}</ref>\n\nSpecies such as ''Grewia'' and ''Euphorbiaceae'' are considered to be fire-sensitive and typically restricted to termite mounds instead of dominating the open savanna <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moe|first=Stein R.|last2=Mob\u00e6k|first2=Ragnhild|last3=Narmo|first3=Anne Kjersti|date=2009-02-11|title=Mound building termites contribute to savanna vegetation heterogeneity|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s11258-009-9575-6|journal=Plant Ecology|language=en|volume=202|issue=1|pages=31|doi=10.1007/s11258-009-9575-6|issn=1573-5052}}</ref> However, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' has been found to be quite widespread throughout the savanna and short-grass areas of the Queen Elizabeth National Park in Uganda. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Midgley|first=Jeremy|date=2009|title=Euphorbia candelabrum juveniles are nursed by spinescent shrubs in short-grass areas of Queen Elizabeth Park, Uganda|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1365-2028.2008.00974.x|journal=African Journal of Ecology|language=en|volume=47|issue=4|pages=788\u2013789|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.2008.00974.x|issn=1365-2028}}</ref> This is an unusual habitat for tall succulents, as they have been proven to typically be poor invaders of frequently burned stands of land. ''Euphorbia candelabrum''<nowiki/>'s success as a tall succulent seems to be a result of over-grazing by African mammals such as the [[Ugandan kob]] (Kobus kob Erxleben) and [[Ugandan water buck|Uganda water\u2010buck]] (Kobus ellipsiprymnus defassa Ogilby) and an overall decrease in intense wildfires.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSome authorities further divide this species into two varieties, ''[[Euphorbia candelabrum var. bilocularis]]'' and ''[[Euphorbia candelabrum var. candelabrum]]''.\n\n''Euphorbia candelabrum'' was used in traditional Ethiopian medicine. Mixed with clarified [[honey]], its sap was used as a purgative to cure [[syphilis]], and when mixed with other medicinal plants as a salve to treat the symptoms of [[leprosy]].<ref>Richard Pankhurst, ''An Introduction to the Medical History of Ethiopia'' (Trenton: Red Sea Press, 1990), pp. 76, 91</ref> This plant currently has negligible commercial value, although [[Richard Pankhurst (academic)|Richard Pankhurst]] documents two different attempts near [[Keren, Eritrea|Keren]] in [[Eritrea]] to collect its gum before 1935, but neither attempt proved commercially viable.<ref>Richard Pankhurst, ''Economic History of Ethiopia'' (Addis Ababa: Haile Selassie I University, 1968), p. 206</ref>\n\nIn terms of agro-forestry purposes, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' has been used in firewood, timber, and fencing. Its wood is light and durable with a number of purposes including roofing, tables, doors, matches, boxes, mortars, musical instruments and saddles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Dangers ==\nWhen structural damage occurs, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' trees release an abundant amount of milky-white latex, which has a rubber content of 12.5%. This latex is extremely toxic due to its skin irritant and carcinogenic [[diterpene]] derivatives, mainly [[phorbol esters]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Uzabakiliho|first=B.|last2=Largeau|first2=C.|last3=Casadevall|first3=E.|date=1987|title=Latex constituents of Euphorbia candelabrum, E. grantii, E. tirucalli and Synadenium grantii|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/s0031-9422(00)84589-6|journal=Phytochemistry|volume=26|issue=11|pages=3041\u20133045|doi=10.1016/s0031-9422(00)84589-6|issn=0031-9422}}</ref> In addition to irritation of the skin and mucous membranes, ''E. candelabrum'' latex may cause blindness if brought into contact with the eyes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nVarious components of ''E. candelabrum'' plants can be utilized as poisons. The Ovaherero people of Namibia use its latex as an ingredient in arrow poison to increase lethality, while the Damara people will often use ''E. candelabrum'' latex extract or freshly pounded branches to poison water holes and streams.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chaboo|first=Caroline S.|last2=Biesele|first2=Megan|last3=Hitchcock|first3=Robert K.|last4=Weeks|first4=Andrea|date=2016-02-01|title=Beetle and plant arrow poisons of the Ju{{!}}\u2019hoan and Hai{{!}}{{!}}om San peoples of Namibia (Insecta, Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae; Plantae, Anacardiaceae, Apocynaceae, Burseraceae)|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4768279/|journal=ZooKeys|issue=558|pages=9\u201354|doi=10.3897/zookeys.558.5957|issn=1313-2989|pmc=4768279|pmid=27006594}}</ref> Its flowers produce nectar but ingestion of ''E. candelabrum'' honey can cause a burning sensation in the mouth and drinking water only intensifies it.\n\nDespite documentation stating that ''E. candelabrum'' latex is extremely toxic and irritating, baboons seem to be unaffected and frequently consume it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Lock|first=J. M.|date=1972|title=Baboons feeding on Euphorbia candelabrum|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1365-2028.1972.tb00862.x|journal=African Journal of Ecology|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=73\u201376|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1972.tb00862.x|issn=1365-2028}}</ref> A study done in Queen Elizabeth Park in West [[Uganda]] found that much of the damage done to ''E. candelabrum'' trees can be attributed to the feeding patterns of baboons. Fresh, young ''E. candelabrum'' branches are broken off by climbing baboons which results in uneven growth. In addition to this, baboon feeding patterns affect the life cycle of ''E. candelabrum'' flowers and often causes sterility in many of the young stems<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n== Medicinal Use ==\nAlthough ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' is known to be quite toxic, it has multiple medicinal uses. Its latex contains highly irritant ingenol diterpene esters which proves to be both harmful and helpful. On top of blistering and irritation, ingenol products demonstrate tumour-promoting activity, causing cells to resist [[apoptosis]] and continue multiplying.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, ingenol is beneficial in the respect that it encourages anti-[[HIV]] and anti-[[leukemia]] cellular activity which protects [[T cell|T-cells]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hong|first=Kee-Jong|last2=Lee|first2=Hak Sung|last3=Kim|first3=Yeong-Shik|last4=Kim|first4=Sung Soon|date=September 2011|title=Ingenol Protects Human T Cells From HIV-1 Infection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24159460|journal=Osong Public Health and Research Perspectives|volume=2|issue=2|pages=109\u2013114|doi=10.1016/j.phrp.2011.07.001|issn=2210-9099|pmc=3766915|pmid=24159460}}</ref> A 1961 study found that three out of 40 mice contracted [[papilloma]] when treated with DMBA only, meanwhile only 3 out of 100 mice developed [[papilloma]] when treated with ''Euphorbia'' latices, indicating that plants from the family ''Euphorbiaceae'' are highly effective anti-tumour agents <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roe|first=F. J. C.|last2=Peirce|first2=Winifred E. H.|date=1961-04-01|title=Tumor Promotion by Euphorbia Latices|url=https://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/21/3/338|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=338|issn=0008-5472|pmid=13742650}}</ref>.\n\nIn addition to being used as a purgative to cure syphilis or a salve to treat leprosy, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' sap has been used in the treatment of coughs, tuberculosis, malaria and HIV infections. It has the ability to be mixed with fat and applied topically to heal wounds, sores, and warts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''E. candelabrum'' latex is an effective abortifacient and a concoction containing pith from the branches may be given to women after childbirth to assist in the expulsion of the placenta.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://herbpathy.com/Action-of-Abortifacient-Cid47|title=Abortifacient Herbs|website=Herbpathy|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> Its roots can be boiled and drinking this fluid is said to help with stomach aches, constipation, and infertility. Ash from the stems has also been used to treat eye infections.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 002.JPG|Branches\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 003.JPG|Cyathia\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 004.JPG|Fruits\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Taxonbar|from=Q2427966}}\n\n[[Category:Euphorbia|candelabrum]]\n[[Category:Flora of Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Flora of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional African medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Euphorbia candelabrum 1.JPG\n|image_caption = ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' in the [[Serengeti]]\n|genus = Euphorbia\n|species = candelabrum\n|authority = [[Carl Georg Theodor Kotschy|Kotschy]]\n|synonyms =\n    {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Euphorbia calycina'' <small>N.E.Br.</small>\n*''Euphorbia confertiflora'' <small>Volkens</small>\n*''Euphorbia murielii'' <small>N.E.Br.</small>\n*''Euphorbia reinhardtii'' <small>Volkens</small>\n    }}\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/kew-78823\n|title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species\n|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n|}}\n\n'''''Euphorbia candelabrum''''' is a [[succulent]] species of [[plant]] in the family [[Euphorbiaceae]], one of several plants commonly known as '''[[candelabra tree]]'''.<ref>{{GRIN | accessdate = 12 January 2018}}</ref> It is closely related to 3 other species of ''[[Euphorbia]]'' in particular; ''[[Euphorbia ingens]]'' in the dry regions of South Africa, ''Euphorbia conspicua'' from western Angola, and ''[[Euphorbia abyssinica]]'' which is native to a number of countries including Sudan, Eritrea, Djibouti, Ethiopia and Somalia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=Euphorbia+candelabrum|title=Euphorbia candelabrum|last=Fern|first=Ken|date=|website=Tropical Plants Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIts Latin name derives from its growth habit, often considered to resemble the branching of a candelabrum. Candelabra trees can be found in dry deciduous and evergreen open wooded grasslands, on rocky slopes and on the rare occasion, termite mounds. As rates of rainfall decrease, so does ''Euphorbia candelabrum''<nowiki/>'s habitat range.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holland|first=P. G.|last2=Hove|first2=A. R. T.|date=1975-03-01|title=The distribution of euphorbia candelabrum in the Southern Rift Valley, Kenya|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02387877|journal=Vegetatio|language=en|volume=30|issue=1|pages=49\u201354|doi=10.1007/BF02387877|issn=1573-5052}}</ref> Trees typically grow to be 12 metres in height however some specimens have been recorded to grow up to 20 metres tall.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''E. candelabrum'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Horn of Africa]] and eastern [[Africa]] along the [[East African Rift]] system. It is known in [[Ethiopia]] by its [[Amharic language|Amharic]] name, ''qwolqwal'', or its [[Oromo language|Oromo]] name, ''{{lang|om|adaamii}}''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Workineh Kelbessa<!-- see [[Habesha name]] -->|title=Traditional Oromo Attitudes towards the Environment: An Argument for Environmentally Sound Development|journal=Social Science Research Report Series|issue=19|year=2001|page=44|url=http://www.publications.ossrea.net/images/stories/ossrea/ssrr-19-p-5.pdf|format=PDF| accessdate={{Date|2014-02-04}} }}</ref>\n\nSpecies such as ''Grewia'' and ''Euphorbiaceae'' are considered to be fire-sensitive and typically restricted to termite mounds instead of dominating the open savanna <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moe|first=Stein R.|last2=Mob\u00e6k|first2=Ragnhild|last3=Narmo|first3=Anne Kjersti|date=2009-02-11|title=Mound building termites contribute to savanna vegetation heterogeneity|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s11258-009-9575-6|journal=Plant Ecology|language=en|volume=202|issue=1|pages=31|doi=10.1007/s11258-009-9575-6|issn=1573-5052}}</ref> However, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' has been found to be quite widespread throughout the savanna and short-grass areas of the Queen Elizabeth National Park in Uganda. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Midgley|first=Jeremy|date=2009|title=Euphorbia candelabrum juveniles are nursed by spinescent shrubs in short-grass areas of Queen Elizabeth Park, Uganda|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1365-2028.2008.00974.x|journal=African Journal of Ecology|language=en|volume=47|issue=4|pages=788\u2013789|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.2008.00974.x|issn=1365-2028}}</ref> This is an unusual habitat for tall succulents, as they have been proven to typically be poor invaders of frequently burned stands of land. ''Euphorbia candelabrum''<nowiki/>'s success as a tall succulent seems to be a result of over-grazing by African mammals such as the [[Ugandan kob]] (Kobus kob Erxleben) and [[Ugandan water buck|Uganda water\u2010buck]] (Kobus ellipsiprymnus defassa Ogilby) and an overall decrease in intense wildfires.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSome authorities further divide this species into two varieties, ''[[Euphorbia candelabrum var. bilocularis]]'' and ''[[Euphorbia candelabrum var. candelabrum]]''.\n\n''Euphorbia candelabrum'' was used in traditional Ethiopian medicine. Mixed with clarified [[honey]], its sap was used as a purgative to cure [[syphilis]], and when mixed with other medicinal plants as a salve to treat the symptoms of [[leprosy]].<ref>Richard Pankhurst, ''An Introduction to the Medical History of Ethiopia'' (Trenton: Red Sea Press, 1990), pp. 76, 91</ref> This plant currently has negligible commercial value, although [[Richard Pankhurst (academic)|Richard Pankhurst]] documents two different attempts near [[Keren, Eritrea|Keren]] in [[Eritrea]] to collect its gum before 1935, but neither attempt proved commercially viable.<ref>Richard Pankhurst, ''Economic History of Ethiopia'' (Addis Ababa: Haile Selassie I University, 1968), p. 206</ref>\n\nIn terms of agro-forestry purposes, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' has been used in firewood, timber, and fencing. Its wood is light and durable with a number of purposes including roofing, tables, doors, matches, boxes, mortars, musical instruments and saddles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Dangers ==\nWhen structural damage occurs, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' trees release an abundant amount of milky-white latex, which has a rubber content of 12.5%. This latex is extremely toxic due to its skin irritant and carcinogenic [[diterpene]] derivatives, mainly [[phorbol esters]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Uzabakiliho|first=B.|last2=Largeau|first2=C.|last3=Casadevall|first3=E.|date=1987|title=Latex constituents of Euphorbia candelabrum, E. grantii, E. tirucalli and Synadenium grantii|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/s0031-9422(00)84589-6|journal=Phytochemistry|volume=26|issue=11|pages=3041\u20133045|doi=10.1016/s0031-9422(00)84589-6|issn=0031-9422}}</ref> In addition to irritation of the skin and mucous membranes, ''E. candelabrum'' latex may cause blindness if brought into contact with the eyes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nVarious components of ''E. candelabrum'' plants can be utilized as poisons. The Ovaherero people of Namibia use its latex as an ingredient in arrow poison to increase lethality, while the Damara people will often use ''E. candelabrum'' latex extract or freshly pounded branches to poison water holes and streams.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chaboo|first=Caroline S.|last2=Biesele|first2=Megan|last3=Hitchcock|first3=Robert K.|last4=Weeks|first4=Andrea|date=2016-02-01|title=Beetle and plant arrow poisons of the Ju{{!}}\u2019hoan and Hai{{!}}{{!}}om San peoples of Namibia (Insecta, Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae; Plantae, Anacardiaceae, Apocynaceae, Burseraceae)|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4768279/|journal=ZooKeys|issue=558|pages=9\u201354|doi=10.3897/zookeys.558.5957|issn=1313-2989|pmc=4768279|pmid=27006594}}</ref> Its flowers produce nectar but ingestion of ''E. candelabrum'' honey can cause a burning sensation in the mouth and drinking water only intensifies it.\n\nDespite documentation stating that ''E. candelabrum'' latex is extremely toxic and irritating, baboons seem to be unaffected and frequently consume it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Lock|first=J. M.|date=1972|title=Baboons feeding on Euphorbia candelabrum|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1365-2028.1972.tb00862.x|journal=African Journal of Ecology|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=73\u201376|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1972.tb00862.x|issn=1365-2028}}</ref> A study done in Queen Elizabeth Park in West [[Uganda]] found that much of the damage done to ''E. candelabrum'' trees can be attributed to the feeding patterns of baboons. Fresh, young ''E. candelabrum'' branches are broken off by climbing baboons which results in uneven growth. In addition to this, baboon feeding patterns affect the life cycle of ''E. candelabrum'' flowers and often causes sterility in many of the young stems<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n== Medicinal Use ==\nAlthough ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' is known to be quite toxic, it has multiple medicinal uses. Its latex contains highly irritant ingenol diterpene esters which proves to be both harmful and helpful. On top of blistering and irritation, ingenol products demonstrate tumour-promoting activity, causing cells to resist [[apoptosis]] and continue multiplying.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, ingenol is beneficial in the respect that it encourages anti-[[HIV]] and anti-[[leukemia]] cellular activity which protects [[T cell|T-cells]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hong|first=Kee-Jong|last2=Lee|first2=Hak Sung|last3=Kim|first3=Yeong-Shik|last4=Kim|first4=Sung Soon|date=September 2011|title=Ingenol Protects Human T Cells From HIV-1 Infection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24159460|journal=Osong Public Health and Research Perspectives|volume=2|issue=2|pages=109\u2013114|doi=10.1016/j.phrp.2011.07.001|issn=2210-9099|pmc=3766915|pmid=24159460}}</ref> A 1961 study found that three out of 40 mice contracted papilloma when treated with DMBA only, meanwhile only 3 out of 100 mice developed papilloma when treated with ''Euphorbia'' latices, indicating that plants from the family ''Euphorbiaceae'' are highly effective antineoplastic agents <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roe|first=F. J. C.|last2=Peirce|first2=Winifred E. H.|date=1961-04-01|title=Tumor Promotion by Euphorbia Latices|url=https://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/21/3/338|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=338|issn=0008-5472|pmid=13742650}}</ref>.\n\nIn addition to being used as a purgative to cure syphilis or a salve to treat leprosy, ''Euphorbia candelabrum'' sap has been used in the treatment of coughs, tuberculosis, malaria and HIV infections. It has the ability to be mixed with fat and applied topically to heal wounds, sores, and warts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''E. candelabrum'' latex is an effective abortifacient and a concoction containing pith from the branches may be given to women after childbirth to assist in the expulsion of the placenta.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://herbpathy.com/Action-of-Abortifacient-Cid47|title=Abortifacient Herbs|website=Herbpathy|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> Its roots can be boiled and drinking this fluid is said to help with stomach aches, constipation, and infertility. Ash from the stems has also been used to treat eye infections.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 002.JPG|Branches\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 003.JPG|Cyathia\nFile:Euphorbia candelabrum 004.JPG|Fruits\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Taxonbar|from=Q2427966}}\n\n[[Category:Euphorbia|candelabrum]]\n[[Category:Flora of Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Flora of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional African medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Aconitum napellus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euphorbia_candelabrum"}
{"title_page": "1973 New Jersey gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 1973 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| country            = New Jersey\n| type               = Presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1969 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| previous_year      = 1969\n| next_election      = 1977 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 1977\n| election_date      = November 6, 1973\n| image1             = [[File:Brendan Byrne 2011 (cropped).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = '''[[Brendan Byrne]]'''\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = '''1,414,613'''\n| percentage1        = '''66.7%'''\n| image2             = [[File:Mike Segal, Skinny D'Amato, Charles Sandman (cropped).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2           = [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]]\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = 676,235\n| percentage2        = 31.9%\n| map_image          = 1973 NJ GovElect Result.svg\n| map_size           = 150px\n| map_caption        = Results by county<br>{{legend|#86B6F2|Byrne 50\u201360%}}\n{{legend|#4389E3|Byrne 60\u201370%}}\n{{legend|#1666CB|Byrne 70\u201380%}}\n{{legend|#CC2F4A|Sandman 60\u201370%}}\n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[William T. Cahill]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Brendan Byrne]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNJ}}\nThe '''1973 New Jersey gubernatorial election''' was held on November 6, 1973. [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Brendan Byrne]] defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]], who defeated the incumbent [[William T. Cahill]] in the Republican primary, with 66.67% of the vote. This is the most recent gubernatorial election in which the Democratic nominee won [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris]] and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties. \n\n==Primary elections==\n[[Primary election]]s were held on June 5, 1973.<ref name=\"state1973\">{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/state/elections/1920-1970-results/1973-primary-election.pdf |title=Candidates for the Office of Governor - State of New Jersey |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |year=1973 |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n\n====Candidates====\n*[[Brendan Byrne]], [[New Jersey Superior Court|Superior Court]] judge\n*Ann Klein, [[New Jersey General Assembly|State Assemblywoman]]\n*[[Ralph DeRose]], [[New Jersey Senate|State Senator]]\n*Frank Forst, union leader and Mayor of [[Jamesburg, New Jersey|Jamesburg]]\n*[[Vito Albanese]], State Assemblyman\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results<ref name=\"state1973\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Brendan Byrne]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 193,120\n| percentage = 45.31\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ann Klein\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 116,705\n| percentage = 27.38\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Ralph DeRose]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 95,085\n| percentage = 22.31\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Frank Forst\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 15,815\n| percentage = 3.71\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Vito Albanese]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 5,460\n| percentage = 1.28\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 426,185\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Republican primary===\n\n====Candidates====\n*[[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]]\n*[[William T. Cahill]], incumbent [[Governor of New Jersey|Governor]]\n*Michael A. Maglio, Essex County Republican Committeeman\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican Party primary results<ref name=\"state1973\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 209,657 \n| percentage = 57.51\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[William T. Cahill]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 148,034\n| percentage = 40.61\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Michael A. Maglio\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 6,881\n| percentage = 1.89\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 364,572\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General election==\n\n===Candidates===\n'''Major party candidates'''\n*Brendan Byrne, Democratic\n*Charles W. Sandman Jr., Republican\n\n'''Other candidates'''\n*A. Howard Freund, American\n*Alfred V. Colabella, Independent \n*Robert Clement, Socialist Labor Party of America\n*John A. Goodson, Libertarian\n*James J. Terlizzi, Sr., Independent Taxpayer's Watchdog\n*Stanley R. Knis, Tax Repeal\n*Kenneth F. Newcombe, Communist\n*Angelo S. Massaro, People's Choice\n*Jack D. Alvino, Independent \n*George Gilk, Defeat Narcotics Crime\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin | title=New Jersey gubernatorial election, 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/state/elections/1920-1970-results/1973-general-election.pdf |title=Votes Cast for the Office of Governor of the State of New Jersey |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |year=1973 |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = [[Brendan Byrne]]\n| votes = 1,414,613\n| percentage = 66.67%\n| change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]]\n| votes = 676,235\n| percentage = 31.87%\n| change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = American Independent Party\n| candidate = A. Howard Freund\n| votes = 6,412 \n| percentage = 0.31%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = Alfred V. Colabella\n| votes = 5,088\n| percentage = 0.24%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Socialist Labor Party of America\n| candidate = Robert Clement\n| votes = 4,249\n| percentage = 0.20%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| candidate = John A. Goodson\n| votes = 3,071\n| percentage = 0.15%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = James J. Terlizzi, Sr.\n| votes = 2,670\n| percentage = 0.13%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = Stanley R. Knis\n| votes = 2,108\n| percentage = 0.10%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Communist Party USA\n| candidate = Kenneth F. Newcombe\n| votes = 2,008\n| percentage = 0.10%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = Angelo S. Massaro\n| votes = 1,898\n| percentage = 0.09%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = Jack D. Alvino\n| votes = 1,843 \n| percentage = 0.09%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n| party = Independent politician\n| candidate = George Gilk \t\n| votes = 1,814\n| percentage = 0.09%\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n| votes =\n| percentage = \n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n|winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n|loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n|swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:New Jersey gubernatorial elections|1973]]\n[[Category:1973 United States gubernatorial elections|New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1973 New Jersey elections|Gubernatorial]]\n[[Category:November 1973 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 1973 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| country            = New Jersey\n| type               = Presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1969 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| previous_year      = 1969\n| next_election      = 1977 New Jersey gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 1977\n| election_date      = November 6, 1973\n| image1             = [[File:Brendan Byrne 2011 (cropped).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = '''[[Brendan Byrne]]'''\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = '''1,414,613'''\n| percentage1        = '''66.7%'''\n| image2             = [[File:Mike Segal, Skinny D'Amato, Charles Sandman (cropped).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2           = [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]]\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = 676,235\n| percentage2        = 31.9%\n| map_image          = 1973 NJ GovElect Result.svg\n| map_size           = 150px\n| map_caption        = Results by county<br>{{legend|#86B6F2|Byrne 50\u201360%}}\n{{legend|#4389E3|Byrne 60\u201370%}}\n{{legend|#1666CB|Byrne 70\u201380%}}\n{{legend|#CC2F4A|Sandman 60\u201370%}}\n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[William T. Cahill]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Brendan Byrne]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNJ}}\nThe '''1973 New Jersey gubernatorial election''' was held on November 6, 1973. [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Brendan Byrne]] defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]], who defeated the incumbent [[William T. Cahill]] in the Republican primary, with 66.67% of the vote. This is the most recent gubernatorial election in which the Democratic nominee won [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris]] and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties. \n\n==Primary elections==\n[[Primary election]]s were held on June 5, 1973.<ref name=\"state1973\">{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/state/elections/1920-1970-results/1973-primary-election.pdf |title=Candidates for the Office of Governor - State of New Jersey |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |year=1973 |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n\n====Candidates====\n*[[Brendan Byrne]], [[New Jersey Superior Court|Superior Court]] judge\n*[[Ann Klein]], [[New Jersey General Assembly|State Assemblywoman]]\n*[[Ralph DeRose]], [[New Jersey Senate|State Senator]]\n*Frank Forst, union leader and Mayor of [[Jamesburg, New Jersey|Jamesburg]]\n*[[Vito Albanese]], State Assemblyman\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results<ref name=\"state1973\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Brendan Byrne]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 193,120\n| percentage = 45.31\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ann Klein\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 116,705\n| percentage = 27.38\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Ralph DeRose]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 95,085\n| percentage = 22.31\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Frank Forst\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 15,815\n| percentage = 3.71\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Vito Albanese]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 5,460\n| percentage = 1.28\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 426,185\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Republican primary===\n\n====Candidates====\n*[[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]]\n*[[William T. Cahill]], incumbent [[Governor of New Jersey|Governor]]\n*Michael A. Maglio, Essex County Republican Committeeman\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican Party primary results<ref name=\"state1973\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Charles W. Sandman Jr.]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 209,657 \n| percentage = 57.51\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[William T. Cahill]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 148,034\n| percentage = 40.61\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Michael A. Maglio\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 6,881\n| percentage = 1.89\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 364,572\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General election==\n\n===Candidates===\n'''Major party candidates'''\n*Brendan Byrne, Democratic\n*Charles W. Sandman Jr., Republican\n\n'''Other candidates'''\n*A. Howard Freund, American\n*Alfred V. Colabella, Independent \n*Robert Clement, Socialist Labor Party of America\n*John A. Goodson, Libertarian\n*James J. Terlizzi, Sr., Independent Taxpayer's Watchdog\n*Stanley R. Knis, Tax Repeal\n*Kenneth F. Newcombe, Communist\n*Angelo S. Massaro, People's Choice\n*Jack D. Alvino, Independent \n*George Gilk, Defeat Narcotics Crime\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin | title=New Jersey gubernatorial election, 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/state/elections/1920-1970-results/1973-general-election.pdf |title=Votes Cast for the Office