{"title_page": "Katrina cough", "text_new": "'''Katrina cough''' is a putative respiratory illness thought to be linked to exposure to [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] and dust after the 2005 [[Hurricane Katrina]] in the [[United States]]. First described by doctors treating patients in the metro [[New Orleans]] area symptoms include [[cough]], [[paranasal sinus|sinus]] [[headache]], [[nasal congestion|congestion]], runny nose, and sore [[throat]], and [[conjunctivitis|pink eye]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wwltv.com/topstories/stories/WWL103105katrinacough.170a5332.html |title=\"Mold, dust contributing to spread of 'Katrina cough,'\" WWL-TV, November 1, 2005 |access-date=November 4, 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051114085604/http://www.wwltv.com/topstories/stories/WWL103105katrinacough.170a5332.html |archive-date=November 14, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>   This condition may make [[immunocompromised]] individuals more susceptible to bacterial [[bronchitis]] and [[sinusitis]]. Most patients are treated with [[antihistamine]]s, nasal sprays, and/or [[antibiotic]]s.\n\nThe Louisiana Office of Public Health conducted a [[case-control study]] of [[emergency department]] visits in New\nOrleans in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.  The OPH distributed a questionnaire to patients seeking treatment for cough, sinus drip, sneezing, wheezing, chest congestion, swollen red and puffy eye(s) and sore throat.  According to the study, state epidemiologists found no increase in the rate of New Orleans-area respiratory illnesses.  Although rates were found to be no different in comparison to state and country rates, the study showed that people with chronic sinus or respiratory symptoms were more affected by the hurricane.   \n\nState epidemiologist Dr. Raoult Ratard disputed the existence of any disease cluster associated with the hurricane in 2006: \"There is no such thing as a single condition such as \u2018Katrina Cough\u2019 that would be different from the bacterial and viral respiratory conditions we would expect to see at that time of year...no such outbreak occurred because of Hurricane Katrina.\"<ref>Bureau of Media & Communications. \"Medical Study Shows No Increase in Respiratory Illnesses Because of Hurricane Katrina\" ''[http://www.dhh.louisiana.gov/offices/news.asp?ID=192&Detail=852 Louisiana Department of Health and Hospitals]''. April 18, 2006. URL accessed on 2006-05-16. [http://www.dhh.louisiana.gov/offices/publications/pubs-192/KatrinaCoughReport.pdf pdf]</ref>\n\nStarting in 2008, Henry Glindmeyer, researcher and professor of pulmonary, critical care and environmental medicine at the [[Tulane University School of Medicine]] is conducting a five-year study to determine if workers in New Orleans face risks from inhalant exposure to minute particles such as mold, fungi or bacteria. The study is funded by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]], an agency of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], which is providing $1.86&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tulane.edu/news/newwave/010208_cough.cfm |title=\"Researcher Seeks Truth About 'Katrina Cough,'\" ''New Wave'', Tulane University, January 2, 2008 |access-date=February 8, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218094238/http://tulane.edu/news/newwave/010208_cough.cfm |archive-date=February 18, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allergy]]\n* [[Coccidioidomycosis]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- To add a reference simply enclose the text you want to appear here inside a <ref></ref> pair in the correct place in the body of the article.-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=1282590 Some Hurricane Survivors Develop 'Katrina Cough']\n\n[[Category:Effects of Hurricane Katrina]]\n[[Category:Health in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''Katrina cough''' is a putative respiratory illness thought to be linked to exposure to [[mold]] and dust after the 2005 [[Hurricane Katrina]] in the [[United States]]. First described by doctors treating patients in the metro [[New Orleans]] area symptoms include [[cough]], [[paranasal sinus|sinus]] [[headache]], [[nasal congestion|congestion]], runny nose, and sore [[throat]], and [[conjunctivitis|pink eye]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wwltv.com/topstories/stories/WWL103105katrinacough.170a5332.html |title=\"Mold, dust contributing to spread of 'Katrina cough,'\" WWL-TV, November 1, 2005 |access-date=November 4, 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051114085604/http://www.wwltv.com/topstories/stories/WWL103105katrinacough.170a5332.html |archive-date=November 14, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>   This condition may make [[immunocompromised]] individuals more susceptible to bacterial [[bronchitis]] and [[sinusitis]]. Most patients are treated with [[antihistamine]]s, nasal sprays, and/or [[antibiotic]]s.\n\nThe Louisiana Office of Public Health conducted a [[case-control study]] of [[emergency department]] visits in New\nOrleans in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.  The OPH distributed a questionnaire to patients seeking treatment for cough, sinus drip, sneezing, wheezing, chest congestion, swollen red and puffy eye(s) and sore throat.  According to the study, state epidemiologists found no increase in the rate of New Orleans-area respiratory illnesses.  Although rates were found to be no different in comparison to state and country rates, the study showed that people with chronic sinus or respiratory symptoms were more affected by the hurricane.   \n\nState epidemiologist Dr. Raoult Ratard disputed the existence of any disease cluster associated with the hurricane in 2006: \"There is no such thing as a single condition such as \u2018Katrina Cough\u2019 that would be different from the bacterial and viral respiratory conditions we would expect to see at that time of year...no such outbreak occurred because of Hurricane Katrina.\"<ref>Bureau of Media & Communications. \"Medical Study Shows No Increase in Respiratory Illnesses Because of Hurricane Katrina\" ''[http://www.dhh.louisiana.gov/offices/news.asp?ID=192&Detail=852 Louisiana Department of Health and Hospitals]''. April 18, 2006. URL accessed on 2006-05-16. [http://www.dhh.louisiana.gov/offices/publications/pubs-192/KatrinaCoughReport.pdf pdf]</ref>\n\nStarting in 2008, Henry Glindmeyer, researcher and professor of pulmonary, critical care and environmental medicine at the [[Tulane University School of Medicine]] is conducting a five-year study to determine if workers in New Orleans face risks from inhalant exposure to minute particles such as mold, fungi or bacteria. The study is funded by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]], an agency of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], which is providing $1.86&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tulane.edu/news/newwave/010208_cough.cfm |title=\"Researcher Seeks Truth About 'Katrina Cough,'\" ''New Wave'', Tulane University, January 2, 2008 |access-date=February 8, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218094238/http://tulane.edu/news/newwave/010208_cough.cfm |archive-date=February 18, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allergy]]\n* [[Coccidioidomycosis]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- To add a reference simply enclose the text you want to appear here inside a <ref></ref> pair in the correct place in the body of the article.-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=1282590 Some Hurricane Survivors Develop 'Katrina Cough']\n\n[[Category:Effects of Hurricane Katrina]]\n[[Category:Health in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katrina_cough"}
{"title_page": "Allied (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 film by Robert Zemeckis}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Allied\n| image          = Allied (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = A man and a woman standing face to face, as if about to kiss\n| director       = [[Robert Zemeckis]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Graham King]]\n* [[Steve Starkey]]\n* Robert Zemeckis\n}}\n| writer         = [[Steven Knight]]\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n* [[Marion Cotillard]]\n* [[Jared Harris]]\n* [[Simon McBurney]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]]\n| cinematography = [[Don Burgess (cinematographer)|Don Burgess]]\n| editing        = {{Plain list|\n* [[Mick Audsley]]\n* Jeremiah O'Driscoll\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plain list|\n* Huahua Media\n* [[GK Films]]\n*[[ImageMovers]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|11|9|[[Regency Village Theatre]]|2016|11|23|United States|2016|11|25|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 124 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 124:28--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/allied-film | title=''Allied'' (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 9, 2016 | accessdate=November 10, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111061841/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/allied-film | archive-date=November 11, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United Kingdom\n* United States\n}}\n| language       = {{Plain list|\n* English\n* French\n}}\n| budget         = $85\u2013113 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=Film L.A.|title=2016 Feature Film Study|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/2016_film_study_WEB.pdf|journal=FilmL.A. Feature Film Study|page=Page 23|date=May 23, 2017|accessdate=June 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731191957/https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/2016_film_study_WEB.pdf|archive-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| gross          = $119.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pittcotillard.htm |title=Allied (2016) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=March 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319105916/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pittcotillard.htm |archive-date=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Allied''''' is a 2016 [[war film|war]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Robert Zemeckis]] and written by [[Steven Knight]]. It stars [[Brad Pitt]] as a Canadian intelligence officer and [[Marion Cotillard]] as a [[French Resistance]] fighter and collaborator who fall in love while posing as a married couple during a mission in [[Casablanca]]. [[Jared Harris]], [[Simon McBurney]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]] also star.\n\nKnight first began developing the story after hearing the story told to him as a 21 year old man. [[Principal photography]] began in February 2016 in London, and would also film in the [[Canary Islands]], used to stand in for [[Morocco]]. [[Joanna Johnston]] acted as costume designer for the film, and would match the designs of the costumes around the character's mindset and situations.\n\nThe film premiered in [[Los Angeles]] on November 9, 2016, and was released in the United States on November 23, 2016 by [[Paramount Pictures]]. It received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for Pitt and Cotillard's performances, in addition to its costume design, but saw criticism for its screenplay and the chemistry between the actors. The film grossed $40.1 million domestic and $119 million worldwide against an approximate $85\u2013113 million budget, becoming regarded as a [[Box-office bomb|box office flop]]. At the [[89th Academy Awards|Oscar]], it would receive a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1942 during [[World War II]], [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Max Vatan, a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] pilot serving on intelligence duties, travels to [[Casablanca]] in [[French protectorate in Morocco|Morocco]] to assassinate a German ambassador. He is partnered with a [[French Resistance]] fighter named Marianne Beaus\u00e9jour, who had escaped from France after her resistance group was compromised and killed.\n\nThe two pose as a married couple and grow close, despite agreeing that in their line of work feelings can get people killed. Marianne, who is trusted by the Germans, secures Max an invitation to the party where they plan to conduct the assassination. On the day itself, they have sex inside a car in the middle of a desert sandstorm, knowing that they might not survive. However, the mission is successful and they both escape. Max asks Marianne to come with him to London and be his wife. The two get married, settle down in [[Hampstead]], and have a baby girl named Anna, who is born during a [[The Blitz|bombing raid]].\n\nA year later in 1943, Max learns from the [[Special Operations Executive]] that Marianne is suspected of being a German spy, having adopted her identity after the real Marianne was killed in France, and that the German ambassador they assassinated was a dissident [[Hitler]] wanted dead. In order to test their suspicions, SOE run a \"blue dye\" operation: Max is ordered to write down a piece of [[Misinformation|false intelligence]] at home, where Marianne can find it. If the information is picked up from intercepted German transmissions, Max must personally execute her, and if he is found to be an accomplice he will be hanged for high [[treason]]. Max is told otherwise to act normally and not conduct his own investigation.\n\nDefiant, Max visits a former colleague named Guy Sangster who knew Marianne; however, Sangster, blinded in the war, cannot confirm her identity. He reveals that resistance fighter Paul Delamare, who worked with Marianne in France, is still alive in [[Dieppe]] and could identify her. Max finds a young pilot named Adam Hunter, gives him a photograph with a \"classified\" note\u2014asking if the woman in the photo is Marianne Beaus\u00e9jour\u2014and instructs him to obtain a \"yes\" or \"no\" answer from Delamare.\n\nMax and Marianne host a house party. Max's commanding officer Frank Heslop comes and tells him that Hunter was killed while waiting on the ground for the answer from Delamare and berates him for his insubordination. Max wonders if what he was told about Marianne is all a test of his loyalty as part of a promotion to [[V-Section]].\n\nThe following evening, Max takes the place of a [[Westland Lysander|Lysander]] pilot and flies to France to meet Delamare, who is being held at the local police station. Max and the local resistance break into the town's local jail, but Delamare is drunk and cannot verify the picture. The delay allows time for the French police officer to alert the Germans, whom Max and the resistance manage to defeat. Prior to leaving, Max is informed by Delamare that Marianne was a talented pianist who had once played ''[[La Marseillaise]]'' in defiance of occupying Germans in the early stages of the war.\n\nBack in England, Max takes Marianne to a local [[pub]] and demands she play the piano. Marianne cannot. She admits she is a spy and forwarded the \"blue dye\" message, which Max left in plain view. She claims her feelings for Max are genuine, and that she was forced back into being a German spy because German agents were threatening Anna.\n\nMax, unwilling to kill his wife, tells her they need to flee the country. He kills Marianne's [[Agent handling|handlers]], a nanny and a jeweller. They drive to a local airbase, but Max cannot get the plane to start before Heslop and the [[Military police of the United Kingdom|military police]] arrive. Max tries to plead his case before the officers, but Marianne tells him that she loves him, asks him to take care of Anna, and then shoots herself. Heslop orders the soldiers present to report that Max executed Marianne as per his orders, so that Max himself will not be punished. After the war, Max moves to a ranch in [[Alberta]] to raise Anna.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Brad Pitt]] as [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Max Vatan\n* [[Marion Cotillard]] as Marianne Beaus\u00e9jour\n* [[Jared Harris]] as [[Colonel]] Frank Heslop\n* [[Simon McBurney]] as S.O.E. Official\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as [[Pilot Officer]] Bridget Vatan\n* [[Daniel Betts]] as [[Flight Lieutenant]] George Kavanagh\n* [[Matthew Goode]] as [[Group Captain]] Guy Sangster\n* [[Anton Lesser]] as Emmanuel Lombard\n* [[August Diehl]] as Captain Hobar\n* [[Camille Cottin]] as Monique\n* [[Charlotte Hope]] as Louise\n* [[Marion Bailey]] as Mrs. Sinclair\n* [[Thierry Fr\u00e9mont]] as Paul Delamare\n* [[Raffey Cassidy]] as Anna Vatan\n* [[Josh Dylan]] as Adam Hunter\n\n==Production==\n===Development and pre-production===\nIn February 2015, it was announced that [[Robert Zemeckis]] was to direct the film, then only known as an untitled [[World War II]] romantic thriller, in which [[Brad Pitt]] would star.<ref name=Feb2015THR>{{cite news|last1=Hayden|first1=Erik|title=Robert Zemeckis to Direct Brad Pitt Romantic Thriller|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/robert-zemeckis-direct-brad-pitt-770867|accessdate=February 7, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207105826/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/robert-zemeckis-direct-brad-pitt-770867|archive-date=February 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Steven Knight]] wrote the original screenplay. It had been a story he had first heard when he was 21 and had travelled with his then-girlfriend to [[Texas]] to visit her family. Her aunt told him the story of how her brother had fallen for a French woman who would become pregnant with his child. He brought her to the [[United States]] where she gave birth. It was discovered she was a German spy, and, on orders, the brother killed her.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Edwards |first1=Shanee |title=Steven Knight\u2019s new film Allied, holds up a mirror to our own divided world |url=https://screenwritingmagazine.com/2016/11/23/steven-knights-new-film-allied-holds-mirror-divided-world/ |publisher=Screenwriting Magazine |accessdate=21 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421190344/https://screenwritingmagazine.com/2016/11/23/steven-knights-new-film-allied-holds-mirror-divided-world/ |archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Knight had desired to make it into a film since that point. While researching for the film, he was never able to find any reference to the story, but did not rule out its accuracy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sauer |first1=Patrick |title=How Accurate Is the Movie \u201cAllied\u201d? |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/how-accurate-movie-allied-180961206/ |publisher=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> He shared the story with Pitt, and from there the production began developing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Brad Pitt & Robert Zemeckis Team On Steven Knight Script|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/brad-pitt-robert-zemeckis-team-on-steven-knight-script-1201367746/|accessdate=February 7, 2015|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206230901/http://deadline.com/2015/02/brad-pitt-robert-zemeckis-team-on-steven-knight-script-1201367746/|archive-date=February 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Radish |first1=Christina |title=Screenwriter Steven Knight on \u2018Allied\u2019, and Why Snoop Dogg Loves \u2018Peaky Blinders\u2019 |url=https://collider.com/steven-knight-allied-interview/ |publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107234930/https://collider.com/steven-knight-allied-interview/ |archive-date=January 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2015, [[Marion Cotillard]] was cast to play a spy along with Pitt, who fall in love during a mission to kill a German official.<ref name=CotillardCast>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Brad Pitt, Marion Cotillard to Play Spies and Lovers in Robert Zemeckis' WWII Movie|url=https://www.thewrap.com/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-to-play-spies-and-lovers-in-robert-zemeckis-wwii-movie/|accessdate=October 25, 2015|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=June 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912124004/http://www.thewrap.com/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-to-play-spies-and-lovers-in-robert-zemeckis-wwii-movie/|archive-date=September 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Alan Silvestri]], who has served frequently as composer for Zemeckis's films, was hired in October.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alan Silvestri to Score Robert Zemeckis' Untitled World War II Spy Drama|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2015/10/21/alan-silvestri-to-score-robert-zemeckis-untitled-world-war-ii-spy-drama/|accessdate=October 25, 2015|work=Film Music Reporter|date=October 21, 2015|author=filmmusicreporter|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025003708/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2015/10/21/alan-silvestri-to-score-robert-zemeckis-untitled-world-war-ii-spy-drama|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2016, [[Jared Harris]] joined the film,<ref name=\"HarrisCast\">{{cite news|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|title=Jared Harris Joins Brad Pitt in Robert Zemeckis' Spy Thriller|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jared-harris-joins-brad-pitt-860172|accessdate=April 1, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=January 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415013044/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jared-harris-joins-brad-pitt-860172|archive-date=April 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> with [[Lizzy Caplan]] cast in March.<ref name=\"CaplanCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Lizzy Caplan Joins Brad Pitt in Robert Zemeckis' Next Movie|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/lizzy-caplan-robert-zemeckis-brad-pitt-1201725703/|accessdate=April 1, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818214520/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/lizzy-caplan-robert-zemeckis-brad-pitt-1201725703/|archive-date=August 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Dunas de Maspalomas.jpg|thumb|left|Locations in [[Gran Canaria]] ([[Maspalomas Dunes]] pictured) were used to double for [[Morocco]].]]\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began in February 2016 in [[London]], with the family home located on the corners of Christchurch Hill and Willow Road in [[Hampstead]].<ref name=\"Mar2016CS\">{{cite news|last=Evry|first=Max|title=Five Seconds of Silence Set Photos with Brad Pitt & Marion Cotillard|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/672069-five-seconds-of-silence-set-photos-with-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard#/slide/1|accessdate=April 1, 2016|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404013809/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/672069-five-seconds-of-silence-set-photos-with-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard#/slide/1|archive-date=April 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Southwark]] was also used for filming, particularly at [[Pullens buildings|Pullens Yard]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Deehan |first1=Tom |title=North-West London offers 1940s backdrop for Brad Pitt\u2019s Allied |url=https://www.thelocationguide.com/2016/11/north-west-london-offers-1940s-backdrop-for-brad-pitt%E2%80%99s-allied/# |publisher=The Location Guide |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117080203/http://www.thelocationguide.com/2016/11/north-west-london-offers-1940s-backdrop-for-brad-pitt%E2%80%99s-allied/ |archive-date=November 17, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> To keep within budget, many of the film's scenes were shot in a former [[Gillette]] factory as, according to VFX supervisor Kevin Baillie, most of the remaining studio space had been occupied by bigger ''[[Star Wars]]'' and [[Marvel Cinematic Universe|Marvel]] films. Production designer Gary Freeman coordinated a construction schedule that allowed for space used for filming a hospital courtyard scene to be redesigned for scenes involving a [[Soho, London|Soho]] pub within the span of two days. Studio space at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]] and [[LH2 Studios]] were also utilized for the London shoot.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Giardina |first1=Carolyn |title='Allied': How Robert Zemeckis' Team Crafted VFX for the World War II Thriller |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/allied-how-robert-zemeckis-team-crafted-vfx-world-war-ii-thriller-950626 |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107170816/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/allied-how-robert-zemeckis-team-crafted-vfx-world-war-ii-thriller-950626 |archive-date=November 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cinematographer [[Don Burgess (cinematographer)|Don Burgess]] stated that all of the more complex scenes for the film were mapped out prior to filming using a style of [[Virtual cinematography|virtual cinematography]], a technique they had used for 2004's ''[[The Polar Express (film)|The Polar Express]]''. Burgess and Zemeckis elected to break the film down into six specific visual appearances to match the changing tone and settings for the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldman |first1=Michael |title=Love and War |url=https://theasc.com/ac_magazine/December2016/Allied/page1.html |publisher=[[American Society of Cinematographers]] |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> In May 2016 scenes set in [[Casablanca]] were shot in [[Gran Canaria]], [[Canary Islands]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brad Pitt To Film Allied Scenes In Gran Canaria |url=http://www.gran-canaria-info.com/en/news/brad-pitt-to-film-allied-scenes-in-gran-canaria |publisher=Gran Canaria Info |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> Freeman stated that filming in the Canary Islands happened as finding locations in Morocco proved a challenge due to the architecture of cities like Casablanca and [[Tangiers]] changing significantly since the time period the film is set in.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stamp |first1=Elizabeth |title=Behind the Scenes of the New Brad Pitt Movie, Allied |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/allied-set-design-filming-locations |publisher=Architectural Digest |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809184436/http://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/allied-set-design-filming-locations |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The airfield scenes were shot at [[RAF Halton]] that was decorated to look like [[RAF Hendon]] during World War II.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/offbeat/brad-pitt-filming-at-raf-halton-1-7353190|title=\u2018Brad Pitt filming at RAF Halton\u2019|website=www.bucksherald.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902224656/https://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/offbeat/brad-pitt-filming-at-raf-halton-1-7353190|archive-date=September 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor when his character spoke French in the film, Pitt worked with Cotillard to help develop his accent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Rachel |title=Marion Cotillard On Filming \u2018Awkward\u2019 Sex Scene With Brad Pitt In \u2018Allied\u2019 |url=https://etcanada.com/news/181235/marion-cotillard-on-filming-awkward-sex-scene-with-brad-pitt-in-allied/ |publisher=[[ET Canada]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601015729/http://etcanada.com/news/181235/marion-cotillard-on-filming-awkward-sex-scene-with-brad-pitt-in-allied/ |archive-date=June 1, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cotillard took [[Weapons training|firearm training]] for the film, but was never fully comfortable holding the weapon. Filming of the assassination scene was interrupted when Cotillard \"freaked out\". To help with her discomfort, Zemeckis instructed her to put the lock on the [[Machine gun|machine gun]] she would use.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirkland |first1=Bruce |title=Marion Cotillard praises Brad Pitt\u2019s French skills in \u2018Allied\u2019 |url=https://torontosun.com/2016/11/19/marion-cotillard-praises-brad-pitts-french-skills-in-allied/wcm/9bb0d9cd-ada8-4230-a843-bd835cb6cd1a |publisher=[[Toronto Sun]] |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Costume design ===\nDesigner and frequent Zemeckis collaborator [[Joanna Johnston]] provided the costume design on the film, and was given free reign by Zemeckis on the designs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kosin |first1=Julie |title=How Brad Pitt & Marion Cotillard Captured the Golden Age of Hollywood in 'Allied' |url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/news/a19163/joanna-johnston-allied-costumes-interview/ |publisher=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607051035/http://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/news/a19163/joanna-johnston-allied-costumes-interview/ |archive-date=June 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She described in an interview that she sought to give the costumes a polished, glossy look. For influence, Johnston paid visits to the [[Imperial War Museum]] in London, a practice she had also done when working on other war set films such as ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]'' and ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/allied-joanna-johnston-robert-zeckis-paramount-oscars-interview-1201869738/ |title=\u2018Allied\u2019 Costume Designer Joanna Johnston On Delivering Polished, Glossy Look For Sweeping Old Hollywood Drama |access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818191436/https://deadline.com/2016/12/allied-joanna-johnston-robert-zeckis-paramount-oscars-interview-1201869738/ |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnston shaped the style of the costumes around the characters, and particular focus was on Marianne, Johnston stated \"\u201cYou never get to the heart of Marianne. I wanted her to look very assured in the first part of the film, in Casablanca. I looked at a lot of French style and fashion plates from the time, and I made her look very clean and graphic. When she goes to London, she takes on a mantle of being a mother and wife, so I put her in warmer tones. But you never really know who she is. Everything becomes a bit more fuzzy in her clothing; the patterns are very different from how they are in North Africa. That hard clarity and sharpness diminishes when she comes to London. But she still has a very French application of style, in the way she puts herself together\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baughan |first1=Nikki |title=Why costume design is so important in 'Allied' |url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/why-costume-design-is-so-important-in-allied/5112408.article |publisher=[[Screen International]] |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> All of the outfits in the film were custom-made for the cast. The silver cross, worn by Brad Pitt in the film, was also custom-made by London-based jeweller Stephen Einhorn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/exploring-the-craft-of-jewellery-making-in-the-film-industry-with-hollywood-jeweller-stephen-einhorn/ |title=Exploring the Craft of Jewellery Making With Hollywood Jeweller Stephen Einhorn |work=Ikon London Magazine |first1=Joe |last1=Alvarez |first2=Tamara A. |last2=Orlova |date=April 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305131316/http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/exploring-the-craft-of-jewellery-making-in-the-film-industry-with-hollywood-jeweller-stephen-einhorn/ |archive-date=March 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its worldwide premiere on November 9, 2016 at the [[Regency Village Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brad Pitt makes his red carpet return at the premiere of 'Allied' |url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Photos/Brad-Pitt-makes-his-red-carpet-return-at-the-premiere-of-Allied/10702/ |publisher=[[United Press International]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925070615/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/Photos/Brad-Pitt-makes-his-red-carpet-return-at-the-premiere-of-Allied/10702/ |archive-date=September 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] released the film on Wednesday, November 23, 2016.<ref name=Nov2015TW>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Brad Pitt, Marion Cotillard WWII Spy Movie Sets Release Date|url=https://www.thewrap.com/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-spy-movie-sets-release-date/|accessdate=November 4, 2015|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=November 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105014312/http://www.thewrap.com/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-spy-movie-sets-release-date/|archive-date=November 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Allied'' grossed $40.1 million in the United States and Canada and $79.4 million in other countries for a worldwide total of $119.5 million, against a net production budget of $85 million.<ref name=BOM/> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' estimated the film lost the studio $75\u201390 million, when factoring together all expenses and revenues, and was listed amongst the years [[Box-office bomb|box office flops]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016s-biggest-box-office-bombs-958780/item/box-office-bombs-gods-egypt-959603|title='Ben Hur' to 'BFG': Hollywood's Biggest Box-Office Bombs of 2016|author=Pamela McClintock|author2=Mia Galuppo|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media|Prometheus Global Media, LLC]]|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713171444/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016s-biggest-box-office-bombs-958780/item/box-office-bombs-gods-egypt-959603|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Allied'' opened alongside ''[[Moana (2016 film)|Moana]]'', ''[[Rules Don't Apply]]'' and ''[[Bad Santa 2]]'' and was expected to gross around $15 million in its opening weekend and $20\u201325 million over its first five days from 3,160 theaters.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/moana-fantastic-beasts-bad-santa-2-allied-thanksgiving-box-office-1201858515/|title=Will 'Moana' Slay 'Fantastic Beasts' Over The Thanksgiving Stretch?|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|accessdate=April 19, 2018|date=November 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822221014/http://deadline.com/2016/11/moana-fantastic-beasts-bad-santa-2-allied-thanksgiving-box-office-1201858515/|archive-date=August 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=preview2>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4244&p=.htm|title='Moana' Sets Sights on $80+ Million 5-Day Thanksgiving Debut|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|last=Brevet|first=Brad|accessdate=April 19, 2018|date=November 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713170257/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4244&p=.htm|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The film ended up grossing $12.7 million in its opening weekend (a five-day total of $17.7 million), finishing 4th at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/moana-fantastic-beasts-tuesday-box-office-thanksgiving-1201859220/|title='Moana' Rings Up $81M+ & Ranks As 2nd Best Thanksgiving Debut After 'Frozen'|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=November 24, 2016|accessdate=November 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820201918/http://deadline.com/2016/11/moana-fantastic-beasts-tuesday-box-office-thanksgiving-1201859220/|archive-date=August 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It remained in fourth place in its second weekend with a gross of $7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/moana-fantastic-beasts-jackie-post-thanksgiving-box-office-weekend-1201863576/|title='Moana' Keeps Fire Going in Chilly December Weekend; 'Manchester' & 'Jackie' Bask in Awards Season Rays|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 4, 2016|accessdate=July 13, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6mX3eYZbF?url=http://deadline.com/2016/12/moana-fantastic-beasts-jackie-post-thanksgiving-box-office-weekend-1201863576/|archive-date=December 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{multiple image|total_width=270|image1=Brad Pitt 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg |image2=Marion Cotillard 1 (July 2009).jpg |footer=The performances of Pitt and Cotillard were given generally mixed reviews from critics, with their chemistry seeing the brunt of the critical derision.}}\nThe [[review aggregate]] site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film an approval rating of 60% based on 247 reviews, and a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.17/10. The site's consensus states: \"''Allied'' has its moments, but doesn't quite achieve epic wartime romance status\u2014a disappointment made more profound by the dazzling talent assembled on either side of the camera.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/allied/|title=Allied (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=July 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211230936/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/allied|archive-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports a normalized score of 60 out of 100, based on 44 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/allied|title=Allied Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=December 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211230942/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/allied|archive-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave a 79% overall positive score and a 56% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=\"opening\"/>\n\n[[Stephanie Zacharek]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' stated that \"Even within this highly synthetic world, Pitt and Cotillard give sturdy, coded performances that feel naturalistic, not phony: They understand clearly that their chief mission is to tap the tradition of melodrama, and they take it seriously. Somehow, almost incomprehensibly, it all works. ''Allied'' looks old but smells new, and the scent is heady.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4577019/allied-movie-review/|title=Review: With Allied, the Old-School Wartime Melodrama Enters the Modern Age|last1=Zacharek|first1=Stephanie|date=November 22, 2016|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128023921/http://time.com/4577019/allied-movie-review/|archive-date=November 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Eric Eisenberg from ''CinemaBlend'' gave the film four out of five, writing: \"Pitt is given what can be called the meatier part, as Max's raw nerves are fully exposed throughout the film as he tries to learn the truth about his wife\u2014but Cotillard's part is the more subtle and challenging, perfectly engulfing Marianne with an enigmatic air that perpetually keeps the audience guessing. They're heavy turns, but Pitt and Cotillard prove again why they're two of the best in the business.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/reviews/1588910/allied|title=Allied|last1=Eisenberg|first1=Eric|website=Cinema Blend|publisher=GatewayBlend Entertainment|accessdate=April 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133159/https://www.cinemablend.com/reviews/1588910/allied|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Rex Reed from ''[[The New York Observer]]'', gave the film four out of four, writing: \"Beautiful, bold and blazing with sex and suspense, ''Allied'' is a gorgeously photographed, intensely romantic, action-packed film by the great director Robert Zemeckis with two titanic star performances by Brad Pitt and Marion Cotillard that delivers something for everyone. If you love classic movies and their potential to sweep you up into a world outside of your own experience, this one will rock your world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observer.com/2016/11/allied-is-a-gorgeous-sweeping-world-war-ii-thriller/|title='Allied' Is a Gorgeous, Sweeping World War II Thriller|last1=Reed|first1=Rex|date=November 21, 2016|website=[[New York Observer]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412101359/http://observer.com/2016/11/allied-is-a-gorgeous-sweeping-world-war-ii-thriller/|archive-date=April 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', Pete Hammond stated that \"Screenwriter Steven Knight has crafted a nifty story that isn't just a mere imitation of something you could imagine [[Ingrid Bergman]] and [[William Holden]] doing, even though wearing a certain hat in one scene Cotillard looks exactly like Bergman in the 1943 classic ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''. This one has all the requisite trappings including Nazis, bombed-out cities, foreign intrigue and impossibly good-looking stars.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hammond|first1=Pete|title='Allied' Review: Brad Pitt & Marion Cotillard Turn Up Movie Star Wattage In Terrific WWII Espionage Thriller|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/allied-review-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-robert-zemeckis-1201858172/|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018|date=November 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222165027/https://deadline.com/2016/11/allied-review-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-robert-zemeckis-1201858172/|archive-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> For [[RogerEbert.com]], Peter Sobcynzki gave the film 4 stars, highlighting the music from [[Alan Silvestri]], the cinematography from [[Don Burgess (cinematographer)|Don Burgess]] and the costume design from [[Joanna Johnston]]. In his summary he wrote \"It is a lovely homage to the kind of entertainment that [[Hollywood]] used to put out in the day without breaking a sweat, while still strong and sure enough to work on viewers who have never seen any of the films to which it pays tribute.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sobcynzki |first1=Peter |title=Allied |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/allied-2016 |publisher=[[RogerEbert.com]] |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228065819/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/allied-2016 |archive-date=December 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nConversely, ''[[The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''{{'}}s Gary Rotstein wrote that notwithstanding \"so many shared plot references [to] ''Casablanca''\", while that film is \"among the greatest films of all time ... the other is about as flat as one of those WWII wall maps on which swastikas denote all the German-occupied parts of Europe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2016/11/23/Movie-review-Allied-is-no-Casablanca/stories/201611230012|title=Movie review: 'Allied' is no 'Casablanca'|first=Gary|last=Rotstein|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=March 13, 2018|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|publisher=PG Publishing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314104512/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2016/11/23/Movie-review-Allied-is-no-Casablanca/stories/201611230012|archive-date=March 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], in his 2 star review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', wrote \"Director Robert Zemeckis is usually known for his zestiness and zippiness; but this is arduous. Screenwriter Steven Knight scripted smart movies such as ''[[Locke (film)|Locke]]'', ''[[Dirty Pretty Things (film)|Dirty Pretty Things]]'' and ''[[Eastern Promises]]'', and there are some nice touches, but it resembles an unconvincing and sluggish pastiche of a war movie\". He would also write critically of Pitt and Cotillard's chemistry, comparing them to \"thesp robots from ''[[Westworld]]'' with some kind of [[Google Translate]] chip implanted in their heads\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |title=Allied review \u2013 Brad Pitt and Marion Cotillard fail to find Blitz spirit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/nov/21/allied-review-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-fail-to-find-blitz-spirit |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226143227/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/nov/21/allied-review-brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-fail-to-find-blitz-spirit |archive-date=December 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' was also critical of Pitt and Cotillard's chemistry, stating \"neither Pitt nor Cotillard is terribly persuasive at conveying the smoldering passions that catch Max and Marianne off guard after their initially circumspect interactions\". This would tie into his criticisms of Knight's screenplay, which he referred to as \"flaccid\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rooney |first1=David |title='Allied': Film Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/allied-review-948331 |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130221543/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/allied-review-948331 |archive-date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver Lyttleton of ''The Playlist'' shared similar sentiments about the script, writing \"Knight\u2019s screenplay would appear to point towards a taut, intimate affair, one that really digs into its two central characters and gets into the white lies and deeper deceit that can take place in wartime and in marriage. But whether by the mandate of a studio wanting \u201ctrailer moments,\u201d or a director who\u2019s always been happy to play with shiny toys, the film is constantly undermined by the actual execution.\" Lyttleton would also be critical of the visual effects and the third act of the film, drawing a comparison of \"malevolently\" splicing scenes of [[Michael Bay]]'s ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' into [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[Notorious (1946 film)|Notorious]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lyttleton |first1=Oliver |title=Brad Pitt & Marion Cotillard Are \u2018Allied\u2019 In Robert Zemeckis\u2019 Engaging, Frustrating WWII Spy Romance [Review] |url=https://theplaylist.net/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-20161121/ |publisher=The Playlist |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127202614/https://theplaylist.net/brad-pitt-marion-cotillard-20161121/ |archive-date=November 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Robert Abele of ''[[TheWrap]]'' write about the screenplay \" Screenwriter Knight fumbles with the plot\u2019s emotional impulses and ticking plot requirements, with neither holding ground long enough to give the movie momentum.\" Abele was also critical of the lead performances and their chemistry, referring to Pitt as \"miscast\" and finding Cotillard ill-fitting of her role.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abele |first1=Robert |title=\u2018Allied\u2019 Review: Brad Pitt and Marion Cotillard Rarely Intrigue as Spies in Love |url=https://www.thewrap.com/allied-review-brad-pitt/ |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930174532/https://www.thewrap.com/allied-review-brad-pitt/ |archive-date=September 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Allied'' was released on [[Digital distribution|Digital HD]] on February 14, 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Allied DVD Release Date|url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7972/allied|website=DVDs Release Dates|accessdate=January 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202010832/http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7972/allied|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and on Blu-ray and [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on February 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Allied|url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m13158/allied|website=[[Movie Insider]]|accessdate=January 23, 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xOVRXPmA?url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m13158/allied|archive-date=February 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Allied official, Miss Sloane, The Americans: Season 4, Your Name & more, lots of new BD cover artwork|url=http://www.thedigitalbits.com/columns/my-two-cents/011917_1300|website=The Digital Bits|last=Hunt|first=Bill|date=January 19, 2017|accessdate=January 19, 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xOVX5vwK?url=http://www.thedigitalbits.com/columns/my-two-cents/011917_1300|archive-date=February 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:small;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n|+ style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Date of ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{nowrap|{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[89th Academy Awards|February 26, 2017]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n|rowspan=3| [[Joanna Johnston]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n| <ref name=\"OscarsVar\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/2017-oscar-nominations-academy-awards-nominees-1201968107/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Complete List |wo